{"parse":{"title":"Wardak Vase","pageid":41679280,"revid":795457344,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\">Wardak Vase</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Wardakvase-BM.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Wardakvase-BM.JPG\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Wardakvase-BM.JPG/350px-Wardakvase-BM.JPG\" width=\"350\" height=\"263\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Wardakvase-BM.JPG/525px-Wardakvase-BM.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Wardakvase-BM.JPG/700px-Wardakvase-BM.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"4000\" data-file-height=\"3000\" /></a><div>Wardak Vase and coins displayed in the British Museum</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Material</th><td>\nCopper alloy</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Size</th><td>\nHeight 17.8 cm</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Created</th><td>\n2nd Century AD</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Present location</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/British_Museum\" title=\"British Museum\">British Museum</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/London\" title=\"London\">London</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Registration</th><td>\nOA 1880-93;CM 1979-2-15-21 to 41</td></tr></tbody></table><p>\nThe <b>Wardak Vase</b> is the name of an ancient globular-shaped buddhist <a href=\"/wiki/Copper\" title=\"Copper\">copper</a> vase that was found as part of a <a href=\"/wiki/Stupa\" title=\"Stupa\">stupa</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Relic\" title=\"Relic\">relic</a> deposit in the  early nineteenth century near <a href=\"/wiki/Chaki_Wardak\" title=\"Chaki Wardak\">Chaki Wardak</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Maidan_Wardak_Province\" title=\"Maidan Wardak Province\">Wardak Province</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Afghanistan\" title=\"Afghanistan\">Afghanistan</a>. The importance of the vase lies in the long <a href=\"/wiki/Kharoshthi\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kharoshthi\">Kharoshthi</a> inscription, which claims that the stupa contained the relics of the <a href=\"/wiki/Buddha\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Buddha\">Buddha</a>. Since 1880, the vase has been part of the <a href=\"/wiki/British_Museum\" title=\"British Museum\">British Museum</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/The_British_Museum_Department_of_Asia\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"The British Museum Department of Asia\">Asian collection</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Discovery\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Discovery</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Description\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Description</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Inscription\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Inscription</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Translation_of_the_Inscription\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Translation of the Inscription</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Discovery\">Discovery</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Wardak_Vase&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Discovery\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The vase, coins and other relics were found by the <a href=\"/wiki/United_Kingdom\" title=\"United Kingdom\">British</a> adventurer and spy <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Masson\" title=\"Charles Masson\">Charles Masson</a> in 1836. Mason unearthed the vase in one of the stupas near the town of Wardak.  The finds were sent to London in 1839, where they became part of the Indian Museum's collection. In 1880, they were transferred to the <a href=\"/wiki/British_Museum\" title=\"British Museum\">British Museum</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Description\">Description</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Wardak_Vase&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Description\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Wardak Vase is <a href=\"/wiki/Spherical\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Spherical\">spherical</a> in shape and made of copper alloy. The vase has a slim neck with an inverted rim and a low flat base. It has a series of three parallel <a href=\"/wiki/Grooves_(archaeology)\" title=\"Grooves (archaeology)\">grooves</a> running around the middle of the vase (with a further two pairs of grooves above and below). Engraved between the upper and middle grooves are four lines of Kharoshthi script that dates the vase and deposit to the year 178 AD. With the vase were found a number of beads and sixty-six coins of the <a href=\"/wiki/Kushan\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kushan\">Kushan</a> Kings <a href=\"/wiki/Vima_Kadphises\" title=\"Vima Kadphises\">Vima Kadphises</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Kanishka_I\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kanishka I\">Kanishka I</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Huvishka\" title=\"Huvishka\">Huvishka</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Inscription\">Inscription</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Wardak_Vase&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Inscription\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The long inscription refers to the Kushan year 51 in the reign of Kanishka I who reigned between AD 110 and 120, but also refers to one of his successors Huvishka, who ruled between AD 146 and 83; it thus provides useful evidence for reconstructing the chronological reigns of Kushan <a href=\"/wiki/Royal_family\" title=\"Royal family\">royalty</a> at the time. The inscription also indicates that the <a href=\"/wiki/Monastery\" title=\"Monastery\">monastery</a> was built by the <a href=\"/wiki/Mahasanghikas\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mahasanghikas\">Mahasanghikas</a>, one of the earliest buddhist schools in India, who were based at <a href=\"/wiki/Mathura\" title=\"Mathura\">Mathura</a>, near Delhi. The vase therefore provides strong evidence for the widespread distribution of Buddhism in <a href=\"/wiki/South_Asia\" title=\"South Asia\">South Asia</a> almost 2000 years ago.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Translation_of_the_Inscription\">Translation of the Inscription</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Wardak_Vase&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Translation of the Inscription\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>A translation of the inscription is described below:\n</p><p>\"In the 51st year, in the month Artemisios, after 15 (days), at this time Vag\u0331amareg\u0331a, son of Kamagulya; he has made his abode here in Khavada (and) establishes in the Vag\u0331amareg\u0331a monastery in a st\u016bpa a relic of the Lord, the \u015a\u0101kya sage.\"\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Wardak_Vase&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Baums, Stefan. 2012. \u201cCatalog and Revised Texts and Translations of Gandharan Reliquary Inscriptions.\u201d In: David Jongeward, Elizabeth Errington, Richard Salomon and Stefan Baums, <i>Gandharan Buddhist Reliquaries</i>, p. 243\u2013244, Seattle: Early Buddhist Manuscripts Project (Gandharan Studies, Volume 1).</li>\n<li>Baums, Stefan, and Andrew Glass. 2002\u2013 . <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://gandhari.org/catalog\"><i>Catalog of G\u0101ndh\u0101r\u012b Texts</i></a>, no. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://gandhari.org/a_inscription.php?catid=CKI0159\">CKI 159</a></li>\n<li>Errington, E., and J. Cribb (eds), The Crossroads of Asia: (Cambridge, <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_India_and_Iran_Trust\" title=\"Ancient India and Iran Trust\">Ancient India and Iran Trust</a>, 1992)</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Wardak_Vase&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?place=105550&amp;plaA=105550-3-1\">British Museum Collection</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/cm/b/bronze_reliquary_and_kushan_co.aspx\">British Museum Highlights</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2189\nCached time: 20180918152007\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.072 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.095 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 371/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 3148/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 368/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 869/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.022/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1,010 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   68.767      1 -total\n 87.35%   60.065      1 Template:Infobox_artefact\n 70.79%   48.680      1 Template:Infobox\n 15.15%   10.416      1 Template:Br_separated_entries\n  9.46%    6.505      1 Template:Reflist\n  3.31%    2.278      1 Template:Template_other\n  3.26%    2.245      2 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:41679280-0!canonical and timestamp 20180918152007 and revision id 795457344\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Pages_using_deprecated_image_syntax"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Asian_objects_in_the_British_Museum"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Buddhist_art"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Reliquaries"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Buddhism_in_Afghanistan"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Afghanistan"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Anc